{{Catalan-speaking world|align=right}}

'''Catalan''' ({{IPA-en|kætəˈlæn}}, {{IPA-en|ˈkætəlæn|}}, {{IPA-en|ˈkætələn|}};&lt;ref&gt;[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/Catalan Catalan] Dictionary.com Unabridged. Random House, Inc. (accessed: March 20, 2010).&lt;/ref&gt; Catalan: '''''català''''' {{IPA-ca|kətəˈɫa|}} or {{IPA-ca|kataˈla|}}) is a [[Romance languages|Romance language]], the [[national language|national]] and the only [[official language]] of [[Andorra]], and a [[official language|co-official language]] in the [[Autonomous Communities of Spain|Spanish autonomous communities]] of [[Catalonia]], the [[Balearic Islands]] and [[Valencian Community]], where it is known as '''[[Valencian]]''' ('''''valencià''''' {{IPA-ca|valensiˈa|}}), as well as in the [[city]] of [[Alghero]] on the [[Italy|Italian]] [[List of islands in the Mediterranean|island]] of [[Sardinia]]. It is also spoken, with no official recognition, in the [[Autonomous Communities of Spain|autonomous communities]] of [[Aragon]] (in [[La Franja]]) and [[Region of Murcia|Murcia]] (in [[Carche]]) in [[Spain]], and in the historic [[Roussillon]] region of southern [[France]], roughly equivalent to the current ''[[Departments of France|département]]'' of the [[Pyrénées-Orientales]] ([[Northern Catalonia]]).

Although recognized as a regional language of the department [[Pyrénées-Orientales]]&lt;ref name=&quot;Charte en faveur du Catalan&quot;/&gt; since 2007, Catalan has no official recognition in France, as French is the only official language of that country, according to the [[French Constitution|French Constitution of 1958]].&lt;ref&gt;French Constitution, 1958: Article 2. The language of the Republic shall be French.&lt;/ref&gt;

==History==
===Middle Ages: origin===
The Catalan language developed from [[Vulgar Latin]] on both sides of the eastern end of the [[Pyrenees]] mountains (counties of [[Roussillon|Rosselló]], [[Empúries]], [[Besalú]], [[Cerdanya]], [[Urgell]], [[Pallars]] and [[Ribagorça]]). It shares origin and features with [[Gallo-Romance]], [[Ibero-Romance]], and the [[Gallo-Italian]] speech types of Northern Italy. Though some hypothesize a historical split from languages of [[Occitan language|Occitan]] typology, the area from Liguria on the present Italian coast to Alicante in Spain can be viewed as a classic [[dialect continuum]], with some perturbation as a result of political divisions and overlay of standard national languages.

As a consequence of the Aragonese and Catalan [[Reconquista|conquests from Al-Andalus]] to the south and to the west, it spread to present-day [[Catalonia]], the [[Balearic Islands]] and most of the [[Valencian Community]].

In the 15th century, during the [[:ca:Segle d'or valencià|Valencian Golden Age]], Catalan literature reached its apex, which was not matched again until [[Renaixença|La Renaixença]], 4 centuries later.

===18th century to the present: France===
{{See also|Language policy in France|La Vergonha}}

After the [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]], a [[royal decree]] by [[Louis XIV of France]] on 2 April 1700, prohibited the use of Catalan language in present-day [[Northern Catalonia]] in all official documents under the threat of being invalidated.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web |url=http://www.crdp-montpellier.fr/cd66/artscult/fichesVauban/cdvauban/PERIODES/moyenagetempsmodernes/chateaucollioureinterdictioncatalan.pdf |title=''L'interdiction de la langue catalane en Roussillon par Louis XIV'' |publisher= &quot;CRDP, Académie de Montpellier}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Right after the Kingdom of France, the centralized [[French Republic]] banned and enacted discriminating policies against the nonstandard languages of France (''[[patois]]''); as Catalan, Occitan or Basque.

The deliberate process of eradicating non-French [[vernacular]]s in modern France and disparaging them as mere local and often strictly oral dialects was formalized with [[Abbé Grégoire]]'s ''Report on the necessity and means to annihilate the patois and to universalise the use of the French language'',&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.languefrancaise.net/dossiers/dossiers.php?id_dossier=66 Abbé Grégoire's ''Report on the necessity and means to annihilate the patois and to universalize the use of the French language'']&lt;/ref&gt; which he presented on June 4, 1794 to the [[National Convention]]; thereafter, all languages other than French were officially banned in the administration and schools for the sake of [[linguistics|linguistically]] uniting post-[[Bastille Day]] France.

Up to this day, the French Republic does not recognize other official languages besides French. Nevertheless, on 10 December 2007, the [[General Council of the Pyrénées-Orientales]] officially recognized Catalan as one of the languages of the department in the Article 1 (a) of its ''Charte en faveur du Catalan''&lt;ref name=&quot;Charte en faveur du Catalan&quot;&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.cg66.fr/202-charte-en-faveur-du-catalan.htm|title=''Charte en faveur du Catalan''}} {{Cite web|url=http://www.cg66.fr/199-la-catalanitat-a-catalunya-nord.htm |title=''La catalanitat a la Catalunya Nord''}} {{Cite web|url=http://www.cg66.fr/culture/patrimoine_catalanite/catalanite/charte.html |title=''Catalanité'' |publisher=cg66.fr |date=2004-07-28 |accessdate=2010-05-16}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; and seek to further promote it in public life and education.

:«Article 1: The General Council of Pyrénées-Orientales officially recognizes, along with the French language, Catalan  as a language of the department ({{Lang|fr|''Le Conseil Général des Pyrénées-Orientales reconnaît officiellement, au côté de la langue française, le catalan comme langue du département''}})».

===18th century to the present: Spain===
{{See also|Language politics in Spain under Franco}}

After the [[Nueva Planta Decrees]], administrative use of and education in Catalan was also banned in the territories of the [[Kingdom of Spain]]. It was not until the [[Renaixença]] that use of the Catalan language started to recover.

In [[Francoist Spain]] (1939&amp;ndash;1975), the use of [[Spanish language|Spanish]] in place of Catalan was promoted, and public use of Catalan was discouraged by official propaganda campaigns. The use of Catalan in government-run institutions and in public events was banned. During later stages of the Francoist regime, certain folkloric or religious celebrations in Catalan were resumed and tolerated. Use of Catalan in the [[mass media]] was initially forbidden, but was permitted from the early 1950s&lt;ref&gt;Marc Howard Ross, [http://books.google.com/books?id=Oe4popSDfW0C&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;hl=en#PPA139,M1 Cultural Contestation in Ethnic Conflict], page 139. Cambridge University Press, 2007.&lt;/ref&gt; in the theatre. Publishing in Catalan continued throughout the dictatorship.&lt;ref&gt;{{citation |last=Thomas |first=Earl W. |year=1962 |pages=43-8 |title= The Resurgence of Catalan |journal=Hispania (vol. 45, March No. 1)|DOI=10.2307/337523}}.&lt;/ref&gt; There was no official prohibition of speaking Catalan in public or in commerce, but all advertising and signage had to be in Spanish alone, as did all written communication in business.&lt;ref&gt;Order from the Excmo. Sr. Gobernador Civil of Barcelona. ''EL USO DEL IDIOMA NACIONAL EN TODOS LOS SERVICIOS PÚBLICOS''. 1940.&lt;/ref&gt;

Following the death of [[Franco]] in 1975 and the restoration of democracy, the use of Catalan increased significantly because of new affirmative action and subsidy policies and the Catalan language is now used in politics, education and the media, including the newspapers ''[[Avui]]'' (&quot;Today&quot;), ''El Punt'' (&quot;The Point&quot;), ''[[Ara (newspaper)|Ara]]'' (&quot;Now&quot;), ''[[La Vanguardia]]'' and ''[[El Periódico de Catalunya]]'' (sharing content with ''[[El Periòdic d'Andorra]]'', printed in [[Andorra]]); and the [[television]] channels of ''Televisió de Catalunya'' (TVC): [[TV3 (Catalonia)|TV3]], the main channel, and [[Canal 33]] (culture channel), [[Canal Super3|Super3]]/[[3XL]] (cartoons channel) as well as a 24-hour news channel [[3/24]] and the sports channel [[Esport 3]]; in Valencia [[Canal 9]], [[24/9]] and [[Punt 2]]; in the Balearic islands [[IB3]]; in Catalonia there are also some private channels such as [[8TV (Catalonia)|8TV]] and [[Barça TV]]. There are also many local channels available in region in Catalan.

==Classification==
The ascription of Catalan to the [[Occitano-Romance languages|Occitano-Romance]] branch of [[Gallo-Romance languages]] is not shared by all linguists, particularly those from Spanish-speaking areas; furthermore, many modern linguists consider any internal classification of the Romance languages a pointless task. According to [[Pierre Bec]], its specific classification is as follows:

*[[Indo-European languages]]
**[[Italic languages]]
***[[Romance languages]]
****[[Italo-Western languages]]
*****[[Western Italo-Western languages]]
******[[Gallo-Romance]]
*******[[Occitano-Romance]]
********Catalan language

Catalan bears varying degrees of similarity to the linguistic varieties subsumed under the cover term ''[[Occitan language]]''. (See also [[Occitan#Differences between Occitan and Catalan|Differences between Occitan and Catalan]] and [[Gallo-Romance languages]]).
Thus, as it should be expected from closely related languages, Catalan today shares many traits with other Romance languages.

==Features==
As a member of the [[Dialect_continuum#Romance_languages|dialect continuum of Romance languages]], Catalan evinces linguistic features similar to those of its closest neighbors ([[Occitan language|Occitan]], [[Aragonese language|Aragonese]]). The following features represent in some cases unique changes in the evolution of Catalan from [[Vulgar Latin]]; other features are common in other Romance-speaking areas.

===Vowel system===
*Common features with [[Gallo-Romance]]:
** Loss of final unstressed vowels except -{{sm|a}} ({{sm|mūrvs}} 'wall' → ''mur'', {{sm|flos}}/{{sm|flōris}} 'flower' → ''flor''); cf. the maintenance of all final vowels except -{{sm|is}} and -{{sm|e}} in [[Ibero-Romance]] ([[Spanish language|Spanish]]/[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] ''muro'' but ''flor''); Italo-Romance maintains all final vowels ([[Italian language|Italian]] ''muro'', ''fiore'').
*Common features with [[Occitan language|Occitan]]:
** Richness of diphthongs and monosyllabic words: {{IPA|[aj]}} ''mai'' ('never'), {{IPA|[ej]}} ''rei'' ('king'), {{IPA|[aw]}} ''cau'' ('s/he falls'), {{IPA|[ew]}} ''beu'' ('s/he drinks'), {{IPA|[ow]}} ''pou'' ('a well'), etc.
[[Image:Homilies d'Organya.jpg|thumb|200px|Homilies d'Organyà: First manuscript in Catalan]]

*Distinguishing features from [[Gallo-Romance]]:
** Preservation of Latin -{{sm|ū}}- as {{IPA|[u]}} ({{sm|lūna}} 'moon' → ''lluna'' {{IPA|[ˈʎunə]}} or {{IPA|[ˈʎuna/ɛ]}}, Occitan ''luna'' {{IPA|[ˈlynɔ]}}, French ''lune'' {{IPA|[lyn]}}).
*Features that distinguish Catalan from [[Spanish language|Spanish]]:
** Maintenance of [[Vulgar Latin]] stressed -{{sm|e}}- and -{{sm|o}}- (short ‹ĕ› and ‹ŏ›), {{IPA|[ɛ]}} and {{IPA|[ɔ]}} respectively ({{sm|terra}} 'land' → ''terra'' {{IPA|[ˈtɛrə]}} or {{IPA|[ˈtɛra/ɛ]}}, {{sm|focvs}} 'fire'→ ''foc'' {{IPA|[ˈfɔk]}}); cf. Spanish diphthongs in ''tierra'' {{IPA|[ˈtjera]}}, ''fuego'' {{IPA|[ˈfweɣo]}}.
*Distinguishing features from [[Occitan language|Occitan]] (generally):
** Diphthong -{{sm|av}}- reduced to open {{IPA|[ɔ]}} ({{sm|cavlis}} 'cabbage' → ''col'', {{sm|pavcvs}} 'not much' → ''poc'').
*Features shared with other Western Romance (Southern Lengadocian, [[Ibero-Romance]]):
** The group -{{sm|act}}- becomes -''et''- ({{sm|lactis}} 'milk' → ''lleyt''* or ''lleit''* → ''llet'', {{sm|factvs}} 'done, fact' → ''feyt''* → ''fet'').

===Consonant system===
*Feature shared with Western Romance (particularly [[Ibero-Romance]]):
** [[Consonant voicing and devoicing|Voicing]] (and [[lenition]]) of intervocalic -{{sm|p}}-, -{{sm|t}}-, -{{sm|c}}- into -''b''-, -''d''-, -''g''- ({{sm|capra}} 'goat' → ''cabra'', {{sm|catēna}} 'chain' → ''cadena'', {{sm|secūrvs}} 'safe' → ''segur'').
*Features shared with Gallo-Romance:
**Preservation of initial {{sm|pl}}-, {{sm|cl}}-, {{sm|fl}}- ({{sm|plicāre}} 'fold' → ''aplegar'' 'to reach', {{sm|clavis}} 'key' → ''clau'', {{sm|flamma}} 'flame' → ''flama''); cf. palatalization of these initial clusters in Spanish ''llegar'', ''llave'', ''llama'' [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] ''chegar'', ''chave'', ''chama''. In the Italo-Romance group this slenderisation generally replaces the second consonant with -''i''- {{IPA|[j]}}; hence Italian ''piegare'', ''chiave'', ''fiamma''.
*Features shared with Occitan (specifically [[Languedocien]]):
** Loss of word-final (originally intervocalic) -{{sm|n}}: {{sm|panis}} ('bread') → ''pa'', {{sm|vinvm}} ('wine') → ''vi''. Unlike in Languedoc and Northern Catalan, plural forms conserve this {{IPA|[n]}}: ''pans'', ''vins''.
** Voiced obstruents undergo [[final obstruent devoicing]]: {{sm|frigidvs}} ('cold') → ''fred'' {{IPA|[ˈfɾɛt]}} or {{IPA|[ˈfɾet]}}. However, final voiceless consonants are voiced before vowels and voiced consonants ([[Assimilation (linguistics)|regressive voicing assimilation]]): ''els homes'' 'the men' {{IPA|[əɫs] + [ˈɔməs] &amp;rarr; [əɫˈzɔməs]}}; ''peix bo'' 'good fish' {{IPA|[ˈpe(j)ʃ] + [ˈbɔ] &amp;rarr; [ˈpe(j)ʒˈβɔ]}}.
*Catalan shows a rare evolution of an early {{IPA|[ts]}} (from Latin -{{sm|d}}-, and -{{sm|c}}- when followed by a front vowel {{sm|e}} or {{sm|i}}, or from the second-person plural verb ending -{{sm|tis}}) to -''u'' {{IPA|[w]}}:
** {{sm|pes}}/{{sm|pedis}} ('foot') → ''peu''
** {{sm|crux}}/{{sm|crvcis}} ('cross') → ''creu'', {{sm|credit}} ('he believes') → ''(ell) creu''
** Verbs in second-person plural ending in -{{sm|tis}}: {{sm|mirātis}} → ''miratz''* → ''mirau'' → ''mireu''/''mirau'' ('you look' [[grammatical number|pl.]]).
*Consonantal palatalisations common to many modern Romance languages, resulting from the combination of a consonant plus [[yod]] (palatal approximant) from a variety of sources:
**{{IPA|/k/ + [[yod]]}} → {{IPA|[ts]*}} → {{IPA|[s]}}: {{sm|caelvm}} ('sky, heaven') → ''cel'' {{IPA|[ˈsɛɫ]}}.
**{{IPA|/ɡ/ + [[yod]]}} → {{IPA|[dʒ]*}} → {{IPA|[ʒ] or [dʒ]}}: {{sm|gelvm}} ('ice') → ''gel'' {{IPA|[ˈʒɛɫ] or [ˈdʒɛɫ]}}.
**{{IPA|/j/}} → {{IPA|[dʒ]*}} → {{IPA|[ʒ] or [dʒ]}}: {{sm|iactāre}} ('lay down') → ''gitar'' {{IPA|[ʒiˈta] or [dʒiˈta(ɾ)]}}.
**Intervocalic {{IPA|/l/ + [[yod]]}} (-{{sm|li}}-, -{{sm|le}}-), -{{sm|ll}}-, -{{sm|cvl}}-, and -{{sm|tvl}}- → ''ll'' {{IPA|[ʎ]}}: {{sm|mvliēris}} ('wife') → ''muller'', {{sm|caballvs}} ('horse') → ''cavall'', {{sm|avricvla}} ('ear') → ''oric'la''* → ''orella'', {{sm|vetvlvs}} ('old') → ''vec'lus''* → ''{{sic|hide=y|vell}}''. In other cases like {{sm|villa}} ('villa') [[gemination]] has been simplified: ''vila'' ('town').
**Intervocalic {{IPA|n + [[yod]]}} (-{{sm|ni}}-, -{{sm|ne}}-), -{{sm|gn}}-, and -{{sm|nn}}- → ''ny'' {{IPA|[ɲ]}}: {{sm|ligna}} ('firewood') → ''llenya'', {{sm|ānnvs}} ('year') → ''any'' (cf. Spanish ''año'').
*Less common among Romance languages, but attested elsewhere:
** [[Palatalization]] of initial {{sm|l}}- ({{sm|lūna}} 'moon' → ''lluna'', {{sm|lvpvs}} 'wolf' → ''llop''). This feature can be found as well in the [[Foix]] dialect of Occitan and in [[Astur-Leonese]].
** Palatalization of -{{sm|x}}- {{IPA|/ks/}} and -{{sm|sc}}- {{IPA|/sk/}} to {{IPA|[(j)ʃ]}} ({{sm|coxa}} 'thigh' → ''cuixa'', {{sm|piscis}} 'fish' → ''peix''). Verbs of the third conjugation (-{{sm|īre}}) that took what was originally an [[inchoative verb|inchoative infix]] (-{{sm|ēsc}}-/-{{sm|īsc}}-) show this palatalization: {{sm|servēscit}} 'serves' (present tense, 3rd person singular indicative) → ''serveix/servix''.
*Other innovations can also be found in other Romance languages:
** Reduction of consonant clusters -{{sm|mb}}-, -{{sm|nd}}- to -''m''-, -''n''- respectively ({{sm|camba}} 'leg' → ''cama'', {{sm|mandāre}} 'to send, to lead' → ''manar''). Also found in [[Gascon language|Gascon]] and southern [[Languedoc]].
** Presence of double consonants: {{sm|septimāna}} ('week') → ''setmana'' {{IPA|[səmˈmanə]}}, {{sm|cvtina}} from {{sm|cvtis}} ('skin') → ''cotna'' {{IPA|[ˈkonːə]}} ('pork rind'), {{sm|modvlvs}} ('mold') → ''motlle''/''motle'' {{IPA|[ˈmɔʎːə]/[ˈmɔlːe]}} ('mold, a spring'), {{sm|athlēta}} ('athlete') → ''atleta'' {{IPA|[əɫˈɫɛtə]}}, {{sm|intelligens}} ('intelligent') → ''intel·ligent'' {{IPA|[intəɫːiˈʒen(t)]}}. Also found in [[Italian language|Italian]].

===Morphology===
* The definite [[article (grammar)|article]]s ''el'', ''la'', ''els'', ''les'' derive from Latin demonstratives {{sm|ille}}, {{sm|illa}}. The older forms ''lo'' ([[grammatical gender|m.]] [[grammatical number|s.]]) and ''los'' ([[grammatical gender|m.]] [[grammatical number|pl.]]) are still common nowadays in some western dialects and in [[Algherese]]. Several varieties of the Catalan language ([[Balearic Islands]], [[Costa Brava]], and [[Tàrbena]]) have maintained an article called ''[[:ca:article salat|salat]]'' (&lt; Latin {{sm|ipse}}, {{sm|ipsa}} →  ''es'', ''sa''), probably formed before the variants of {{sm|ille}} developed. Singular articles are elided before vowel-initial words, in speech and writing: ''el'' + ''home'' &gt; ''l'home'' 'the man', ''la'' + ''hora'' &gt; ''l'hora'' 'the time'.
* [[Possessive adjectives]] are formed with the definite article (''el meu gos'' 'my dog') like in Italian (''il mio cane''), Portuguese (''o meu cão'') and in many Occitan dialects (Languedocien and Pyrenean Gascon). Weak forms of possessive adjectives (''mon, ma, mos, mes,'' etc.) are fossilized for certain usages, as close familiar relatives or in order to express a high degree of affection (for instance: ''mon pare'' 'my dad', ''ma mare'' 'my mum'; in Valencian ''ma casa'' 'my home', ''ma vida'' 'my life'). Also note the postposition of the possessive to express particular nuances, e.g. ''casa meva'' ('my home', literally 'a house of mine') as different from ''la meva casa'' ('my house').
*Plurals are formed in a number of ways:
** ''-a'' becomes -''es''  (e.g. ''casa'' 'house' &gt; ''cas&lt;u&gt;es&lt;/u&gt;'').
**Most consonant- and vowel-final words (except -''a'') add -''s'': ''noi'' 'boy' &gt; ''noi&lt;u&gt;s&lt;/u&gt;'', ''detall'' 'detail' &gt; ''detall&lt;u&gt;s&lt;/u&gt;''
**Words ending in sibilants (-''s'', -''ç'', -''x'', -''ig'') form plurals with -''os'': ''gos'' 'dog' &gt; ''goss&lt;u&gt;os&lt;/u&gt;'', ''peix'' 'fish' &gt; ''peix&lt;u&gt;os&lt;/u&gt;''. Some plural words with -''ig'' may alternate forming plural by adding -''os'' or a silent -''s'': ''raig'' 'ray' &gt; ''raj&lt;u&gt;os&lt;/u&gt;''/''raig&lt;u&gt;s&lt;/u&gt;''.
**Words ending in sibilant clusters (-''sc'', -''st'', -''xt'') may form plurals by adding -''os'' or -''s'': ''bosc'' 'forest' &gt; ''bosc&lt;u&gt;os&lt;/u&gt;''/''bosc&lt;u&gt;s&lt;/u&gt;'', ''aquest'' 'this' &gt; ''aquest&lt;u&gt;os&lt;/u&gt;''/''aquest&lt;u&gt;s&lt;/u&gt;''.
**Words ending in a stressed vowel often take -''ns'': ''pi'' 'pine' &gt; ''pi&lt;u&gt;ns&lt;/u&gt;'', ''cinturó'' 'belt' &gt; ''cinturo&lt;u&gt;ns&lt;/u&gt;'' (but ''esquí'' 'ski' &gt; ''esquís'', ''tabú'' 'taboo' &gt; ''tabús''). In Western Catalan dialects, some particular words ending in unstressed vowels may also form plural by adding -''ns'': ''home'' 'man' &gt; ''hòme&lt;u&gt;ns&lt;/u&gt;'' (from Latin {{sm|homo}} &gt; {{sm|homini}}).
* Partitive: While Catalan patterns with Ibero-Romance in the lack of a partitive article (e.g. ''vull pa'' 'I want some bread', cf. Spanish ''quiero pan'' but French ''je veux du pain''), it does have a partitive pronoun, like in Gallo-Romance languages: ''jo &lt;u&gt;en&lt;/u&gt; tinc tres'' 'I have three of them' (Spanish ''tengo tres'' but French ''j'en ai trois'').
* The construction used to express [[Grammatical aspect|punctual/perfective aspect]] in the past tense is one of the most distinctive features of Catalan. It is a periphrasis formed with a special conjugation of ''anar'' ('to go'), that comes from the Latin verb {{sm|vadere}}, plus the infinitive form of the main verb. For example: ''jo &lt;u&gt;vaig&lt;/u&gt; dir'' ('I said'). This construction has almost completely replaced the historical simple past form (''jo diguí''), which corresponds to the Spanish preterit or French passé simple.

===Lexicon===
The basic vocabulary shows more affinities with the Gallo-Romance group than with Ibero-Romance.&lt;ref&gt;{{citation |last=Wheeler |first=Max H. |year=2006 |title=Catalan, in the [[Encyclopedia of Language and Linguistics]]}}.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{citation |last=Colón |first=Germà |year=1993 |title=El lèxic català dins la Romània |collection=Biblioteca Lingüística Catalana |publisher=Universitat de València |place=Valencia |isbn=84-370-1327-5}}.&lt;/ref&gt; These similarities are most notable with Occitan (examples below are from Languedocian).

* {{sm|fenestra}} &gt; ''finestra'' 'window' ([[Occitan language|Oc.]] ''fenèstra/finèstra'', [[french language|Fr.]] ''fenêtre'', [[Italian language|It.]] ''finestra'') vs {{sm|ventvs}} &gt; ''ventana'' ([[Spanish language|Sp.]]), ''janela'' ([[Portuguese language|Pt.]])
* {{sm|mandvcāre}} &gt; ''menjar'' 'to eat' ([[Occitan language|Oc.]] ''manjar'', [[French language|Fr.]] ''manger'', [[Italian language|It.]] mangiare) vs {{sm|comedere}} &gt; ''comer'' ([[Spanish language|Sp]] and [[Portuguese language|Pt.]])
* {{sm|matvtīnvs}} &gt; ''matí'' 'morning' ([[Occitan language|Oc.]] ''matin'', [[French language|Fr.]] ''matin'', [[Italian language|It.]] ''mattino/mattina'') vs {{sm|hora maneāna}} &gt; ''mañana'' ([[Spanish language|Sp.]]), ''amanhã'' ([[Portuguese language|Pt.]])
* {{sm|parabolāre}} &gt; ''parlar'' 'to speak' ([[Occitan language|Oc.]] ''parlar'', [[French language|Fr.]] ''parler'', [[Italian language|It.]] ''parlare'') vs {{sm|fābvlāre}} &gt; ''hablar'' ([[Spanish language|Sp.]]), ''falar'' [[Portuguese language|Pt.]])
* {{sm|tabvla}} &gt; ''taula'' 'table' ([[Occitan language|Oc.]]  ''taula'', [[French language|Fr.]] ''table'', [[Italian language|It.]] ''tavola'') vs {{sm|mensa}} &gt; ''mesa'' ([[Spanish language|Sp.]] and [[Portuguese language|Pt.]])

===Writing system===
{{Main|Catalan orthography}}
The Catalan writing system has a number of distinctive features. The graph ‹l·l› (named ''ela geminada'' 'geminated-l') is composed of an [[interpunct]] (or middot) between two ‹l› (e.g. ''intel·ligent'' 'intelligent' or ''novel·la'' 'novel') and is used to distinguish phonetically {{IPA|[ɫɫ]}} from {{IPA|[ʎ]}} (written ‹ll› like in Spanish). Another special digraph is ‹ny› {{IPA|[ɲ]}}, found in [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], [[Malay language|Malay]] and in some African languages (e.g. ''banys'' 'baths'). Also of note is the final digraph ‹-ig›, pronounced {{IPA|[tʃ]}} after a vowel (e.g. ''faig'' 'I do', ''maig'' 'May', ''raig'' 'ray', ''roig'' 'red', ''veig'' 'I see', ''puig'' 'hill') and {{IPA|[itʃ]}} after a consonant (e.g. ''mig'' 'half', ''desig'' 'desire'). The combination of  ‹t› + nasal or lateral consonant is pronounced as a [[gemination|geminate]] of the second consonant: ‹tm› {{IPA|[mm]}}, ‹tn› {{IPA|[nn]}}, ‹tl› {{IPA|[ɫɫ]}} and ‹tll› {{IPA|[ʎʎ]}} (e.g. ''setmana'' 'week', ''cotna'' 'pork rind', ''Betlem'' 'Betlehem', ''bitllet'' 'bank note'), whereas ‹t› + sibilant consonant indicates [[affricate consonant|affrication]]: ‹tx› {{IPA|[tʃ]}}, ‹ts› {{IPA|[ts]}}, ‹tz› {{IPA|[dz]}}, ‹tg› and ‹tj› {{IPA|[dʒ]}} (e.g. ''potser'' 'maybe', ''dotze'' 'twelve', ''jutge'' 'judge', ''platja'' 'beach'). In addition, Catalan spelling utilizes ‹ç› (called ''[[c-cedilla|ce trencada]]'', literally 'broken-c') when ‹c› takes the soft sound {{IPA|[s]}} before ‹a›, ‹o› and ‹u› (e.g. ''caça'' 'hunt'). Furthermore, the letter ‹x› can represent different sibilant sounds; {{IPA|[ks]}} (e.g. ''fixar'' 'fix'), {{IPA|[gz]}} (e.g. ''exacte'' 'exact'), {{IPA|[ʃ]}} (e.g. ''xarxa'' 'net') and dialectally {{IPA|[tʃ]}} (e.g. ''xiquet'' 'boy'), while the digraph ‹ix› always represents {{IPA|[(j)ʃ]}} (e.g. ''calaixos'' 'drawers') or {{IPA|[(j)ʒ]}} (e.g. ''peix al forn'' 'oven fish').

==Geographic distribution==
===Països Catalans===
Catalan is spoken in:
*[[Andorra]] (''Principat d'Andorra''), a [[sovereign state]] where Catalan is the [[national language|national]] and only [[official language]].
*[[Catalonia]] (''Catalunya''), in [[Spain]].
*Most of the [[Valencian Community]] (''Comunitat Valenciana'', also known as ''País Valencià''), in [[Spain]], where it is called [[Valencian]] (''valencià'').
*[[La Franja]], an adjacent strip of [[Aragon]], in [[Spain]] (in particular the ''[[Comarcas of Aragon|comarques]]'' of [[Ribagorça]], [[Llitera]], [[Baix Cinca]], and [[Matarranya]]).
*[[Balearic Islands]] (''Illes Balears''), in [[Spain]].
*[[Northern Catalonia]] (''Catalunya Nord'': name used officially for the first time on 10 December 2007 by the General Council of the [[Pyrénées-Orientales]]), in [[France]].
*The city of [[Alghero]] (''l'Alguer'') in [[Sardinia]], [[Italy]].
*A small region in [[Region of Murcia|Murcia]], [[Spain]], known as [[Carche]] (''El Carxe'').

These territories are referred as [[Catalan Countries]] (''Països Catalans''), a denomination based on cultural affinity and common heritage, that has also had a subsequent political interpretation but no official status.

