==Grammar==
{{Main|Catalan grammar}}
The first descriptive and normative grammar book of modern Catalan was written by [[Pompeu Fabra]] in 1918. In 1995, a new grammar by [[Antoni Maria Badia i Margarit]] was published, which also documents the Valencian and Balearic varieties.

The grammar of Catalan follows the general pattern of Western Romance languages. The primary [[word order]] is [[Subject Verb Object|SVO]] (Subject-Verb-Object).&lt;ref&gt;[http://wals.info/languoid/lect/wals_code_ctl The World Atlas of Language Structures]. wals.info.&lt;/ref&gt;

Substantives and adjectives are not declined by case, as in Classical Latin. There are two [[grammatical gender]]s—masculine and feminine.

Grammatical [[article (grammar)|article]]s developed from Latin [[demonstrative]]s. The form of the article depends on the gender and the number of the subject and the first sounds of the word and can be combined with prepositions that precede them. A unique feature of Catalan is a definite article that may precede [[personal names]] in certain contexts. Its basic form is ''en'' and it can change according to its environment (note [[clitic]] ''en'' has also other lexical meanings). One of the common usages of this article is in the word ''can'', a combination of ''la casa'' shortened to ''ca'' ('house', as [[French language|French]] ''chez'') and ''en'', which here means 'the'. For example ''la casa d'en Sergi'' becomes ''Can Sergi'' meaning 'the house of Sergi', 'Sergi's house'. Note here, other articles (''el, la, els, les'') can also be used with personal names like in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], as ''la Maria'' (or ''na Maria'').

Verbs are conjugated according to tense and mood similarly to other Western Romance languages—present and simple preterite are based on classical Latin, future is formed from infinitive followed by the present form of the auxiliary verb ''haver'' (written together and not considered periphrastic), and periphrastic tenses are formed from the conjugated auxiliary verbs ''haver'' ('to have') and ''ésser'' ('to be') followed by the past participle. A unique tense in Catalan is the &quot;periphrastic simple preterite,&quot; which is formed of ''vaig'', ''vas'' (or ''vares''), ''va'', ''vam'' (or ''vàrem''), ''vau'' (or ''vàreu'') and ''van'' (there is the usual wrong idea these forms are the conjugated forms of ''anar'', which means 'to go'), which is followed by the infinitive of the verb.  Thus, ''jo vaig parlar'' (or more simply ''vaig parlar'') means 'I spoke'.

Nominative pronouns are often omitted, as the subject can be usually derived from the conjugated verb. The Catalan rules for combination of the object pronoun [[clitic]]s with verbs, articles and other pronouns are significantly more complex than in most other Romance languages; see [[Weak pronouns in Catalan]].

==Catalan names==
{{main|Catalan names}}

Catalan naming customs are similar to those of Spain and [[Portugal]]; people receive two last names – their father's and their mother's – which are separated by the particle ''i'', meaning 'and' (in Spanish the equivalent particle is written ''y'', but often omitted altogether).

For example, the full name of the architect [[Antoni Gaudí]] is Antoni ''Gaudí i Cornet'' after his parents: Francesc ''Gaudí'' i Serra and Antònia ''Cornet'' i Bertran, meaning he was son of ''Gaudí'' and ''Cornet''.

==Examples==
{{IPA notice}}
Some phrases in the [[Central Catalan|Central dialect]] (Barcelona and outskirts):

* Catalan: ''català'' {{IPA|[kətəˈɫa]}}
* Hello: ''hola'' {{IPA|[ˈɔɫə]}}
* Good-bye: ''adéu'' {{IPA|[əˈðew]}}; ''adéu-siau'' {{IPA|[əˈðew siˈaw]}}; ''siau'' {{IPA|[siˈaw]}}; '''déu'' {{IPA|[ˈdew]}} (colloquial use)
* Please: ''si us plau'' or ''sisplau'' {{IPA|[sisˈpɫaw]}}; ''per favor'' {{IPA|[ˈpəɾ fəˈβo]}}
* Thank you: ''gràcies'' {{IPA|[ˈɡɾasiəs]}}; ''mercès'' {{IPA|[məɾˈsɛs]}}; ''merci'' {{IPA|[ˈmɛɾsi]}} (colloquial use)
* Sorry: ''perdó'' {{IPA|[pəɾˈðo]}}, ''em sap greu'' {{IPA|[əmsabˈɡɾew]}}; ''ho sento'' {{IPA|[uˈsentu]}}
* This one: ''aquest'' {{IPA|[əˈkɛt]}} (masc.); ''aquesta'' {{IPA|[əˈkɛstə]}} (fem.)
* How much?: ''quant val?'' {{IPA|[ˈkwamˈbaɫ]}}; ''quant és?'' {{IPA|[ˈkwanˈtes]}}
* Yes: ''sí'' {{IPA|[ˈsi]}}
* No: ''no'' {{IPA|[ˈno]}}
* I don't understand (it): ''no ho entenc'' {{IPA|[ˈnowənˈteŋ]}}
* Where's the bathroom?: ''On és el bany?'' {{IPA|[ˈoˈnezəɫˈβaɲ]}}; ''On és el lavabo?'' {{IPA|[ˈoˈnezəɫɫəˈβaβu]}}; ''On és el servei?'' {{IPA|[ˈoˈnezəɫsəɾˈβɛj]}}
* Generic toast: ''salut!'' {{IPA|[səˈɫut]}};
* Bless you! (after sneezing): ''Jesús'' {{IPA|[ʒəˈzus]}}; ''salut!'' {{IPA|[səˈɫut]}}
* Do you speak Catalan? (informal singular, addressing as ''tu'' using 2nd person singular): ''Que parles català?'' {{IPA|[kəˈpaɾɫəz kətəˈɫa]}}
* Do you speak Catalan? (formal singular, addressing as ''vostè'' using 3rd person singular): ''Que parla català?'' {{IPA|[kəˈpaɾɫə kətəˈɫa]}}
* Do you speak Catalan? (informal plural, addressing as ''vosaltres'' using 2nd person plural): ''Que parleu català?'' {{IPA|[kəpəɾˈɫɛw kətəˈɫa]}}
* Do you speak Catalan? (formal plural, addressing as ''vostès'' using 3rd person plural): ''Que parlen català?'' {{IPA|[kəˈpaɾɫən kətəˈɫa]}}

The same phrases pronounced as in the ''[[Valencian#Sub-varieties of Valencian|standard Valencian]]'':

*Valencian: ''valencià'' {{IPA|[valensiˈa]}}
*Hello: ''hola'' {{IPA|[ˈɔla]}}
*Good-bye: ''adéu'' {{IPA|[aˈðew]}}
*Please: ''per favor'' {{IPA|[peɾ faˈvoɾ]}}
*Thank you: ''gràcies'' {{IPA|[ˈɡɾasies]}}
*Sorry: ''perdó'' {{IPA|[peɾˈðo]}}; ; ''ho sent'' {{IPA|[uˈsent]}} or {{IPA|[uˈseŋk]}}
* This one: ''este'' {{IPA|[ˈeste]}} (masc.); ''esta'' {{IPA|[ˈesta]}} (fem.)
*How much?: ''quant val?'' {{IPA|[ˈkwaɱˈvaɫ]}}; ''quant és?'' {{IPA|[ˈkwanˈtes]}}
*Yes: ''sí'' {{IPA|[ˈsi]}}
*No: ''no'' {{IPA|[ˈno]}}
*I don't understand: ''no ho entenc'' {{IPA|[ˈnowanˈteŋ]}}
*Where's the bathroom?: ''on és el bany?'' {{IPA|[oˈnezeɫˈβaɲ]}}
*Generic toast: ''salut!'' {{IPA|[saˈlut]}}
*Bless you! (after sneezing): ''Jesús!'' {{IPA|[dʒeˈzus]}}; ''salut!'' {{IPA|[saˈlut]}}
*Do you speak Valencian?: ''parles valencià?'' {{IPA|[ˈpaɾlez valensiˈa]}}

==English words of Catalan origin==
&lt;!--Please don't add &quot;cul de sac&quot; unless you have a reliable source!
Si us plau, no afegiu &quot;cul de sac&quot; si no teniu un font fiable!--&gt;

* [[Aubergine]], from Catalan ''albergínia'' or ''albergina''&lt;ref name=&quot;Websters-Third&quot;&gt;{{Cite book| title=Webster's Third New International Dictionary | publisher=Merriam-Webster, inc. | year=1993 | editor=[[Philip Babcock Gove]] | isbn=3-8290-5292-8}}&lt;/ref&gt; through [[French language|French]]
* [[Barracks]], from Old Catalan ''barraca'' (hut) through [[French language|French]] ''baraque''.&lt;ref name=&quot;Collins&quot;&gt;{{Cite book| title=Collins English Dictionary | publisher=HarperCollins Publishers | location= | year=1991 | editor= | isbn=0-00-433286-5 | url=}}&lt;/ref&gt; Another term [[barracoon]], from Catalan ''barraca'' (hut) through [[Spanish language|Spanish]] ''barracón''&lt;ref name=&quot;Collins&quot;/&gt;
* [[:wikt:surge|Surge]], from [[Middle French]], which took it from Old Catalan ''surgir''&lt;ref name=&quot;Websters-Third&quot;/&gt;
* [[Paella]], Valencian Catalan, via [[Old French]] ''paele'', ultimately from Latin ''patella'' (small dish)&lt;ref name=&quot;Websters-Third&quot; /&gt;

